Title: Pitch Perfect 2 - Official Trailer 2 (HD)
Comment: I was so disappointed with the sequel. The highlight was 'Das Sound Machine'. The trailers tone and pacing was better than the movie itself. I did not find the subplots compelling and actually detracted from the primary story. I also noted a majority of the dialgoue and humor written for the Bellas fell flat or did not quite execute well. Whereas Das Sound Machine had great timing and although they had less screen time seemed almost superior as characters to the Bellas. Elements from the first movie were incorporated with new ones and yet it all seemed a bit tired, especially with the girls. Anything newly tried for the sequel also came across as awkward or hit and miss. This cinematic follow-up could have been great but it ended up being so mediocre.

Comment:
People say this movie needs more Skylar Astin. I understand that. Here's a solution.

Instead of having Beca and Skylar still be together after three years even though they have no chemistry, have them realistically and peacefully break up during the timeskip, deciding just to be friends. Focus the movie around developing Beca and Cloe's romantic chemistry. Have the main subplot be about Skylar's character development post-Beca and finding a new love interest.

This will not only make him a more interesting character, but if he has an arc that doesn't center around Beca he would have a lot more screen time and he would actually be an interesting character with an arc that I can actually LIKE in this movie. Because I hated his character in the first movie, he was kind of a douche. And Skylar Astin is too damn beautiful not to have a better character to play, more screen time, and a better arc.

Basically what I'm saying is the Skylar Astin Solution starts with having him and Beca decide to be friends during the timeskip, thus giving the character room to grow outside of her story and providing Bechloe with the opportunity to be developed into the relationship it has the potential to be. The story and characters would feel a lot more thought-out and genuine this way. The movie could still also focus on Fat Amy and Bumper and even have blips of Emily and whatshisface if you replace all those scenes where Emily (a new character we don't care about) takes up precious screen time that could be better utilized developing pre-existing characters.

None of this happened, but oh well.
